 of an expression involving only constants at compile-time rather than generating the code to compute the value at run-time. There are multiple levels of constant folding in .NET, with some constant folding performed by the C# compiler and some constant folding performed by the JIT compiler. For example, given the C# code:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2630, 2636], level=0, children=None, content='[Benchmark]\npublic int A() => 3 + (4 * 5);\n[Benchmark]\npublic int B() => A() * 2;\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2637, 2638], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2637, 2638], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='the C# compiler will generate IL for these methods like the following:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='the C# compiler will generate IL for these methods like the following:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2639, 2656], level=0, children=None, content='.method public hidebysig instance int32 A () cil managed \n{\n .maxstack 8\n IL_0000: ldc.i4.s 23\n IL_0002: ret\n}\n.method public hidebysig instance int32 B () cil managed \n{\n .maxstack 8\n IL_0000: ldarg.0\n IL_0001: call instance int32 Program::A()\n IL_0006: ldc.i4.2\n IL_0007: mul\n IL_0008: ret\n}\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2657, 2658], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2657, 2658], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="You can see that the C# compiler has computed the value of 3 + (4*5), as the IL for method A simply contains the equivalent of return 23;. However, method B contains the equivalent of return A() * 2;, highlighting that the constant folding performed by the C# compiler was intramethod only. Now here's what the JIT generates:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="You can see that the C# compiler has computed the value of 3 + (4\\*5), as the IL for method A simply contains the equivalent of return 23;. However, method B contains the equivalent of return A() \\* 2;, highlighting that the constant folding performed by the C# compiler was intramethod only. Now here's what the JIT generates:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2659, 2669], level=0, children=None, content='; Program.A()\n mov eax,17\n ret\n; Total bytes of code 6\n; Program.B()\n mov eax,2E\n ret\n; Total bytes of code 6\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2670, 2671], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2670, 2671], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="The assembly for method A isn't particularly interesting; it's just returning that same value 23 (hex 0x17). But method B is more interesting. The JIT has inlined the call from B to A, exposing the contents of A to B, such that the JIT effectively sees the body of B as the equivalent of return 23 * 2;. At that point, the JIT can do its own constant folding, and it transforms the body of B to simply return 46 (hex 0x2e). Constant propagation is intricately linked to constant folding and is essentially just the idea that you can substitute a constant value (typically one computed via constant folding) into further expressions, at which point they may also be able to be folded.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="The assembly for method A isn't particularly interesting; it's just returning that same value 23 (hex 0x17). But method B is more interesting. The JIT has inlined the call from B to A, exposing the contents of A to B, such that the JIT effectively sees the body of B as the equivalent of return 23 \\* 2;. At that point, the JIT can do its own constant folding, and it transforms the body of B to simply return 46 (hex 0x2e). Constant propagation is intricately linked to constant folding and is essentially just the idea that you can substitute a constant value (typically one computed via constant folding) into further expressions, at which point they may also be able to be folded.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2672, 2673], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2672, 2673], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='The JIT has long 