te1() => Value + Value + Value + Value + Value;\n[Benchmark]\npublic int Compute2() => SomethingElse() + Value + Value + Value + Value + Value;\nprivate static int Value => 16;\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2772, 2776], level=0, children=None, content='[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.NoInlining)]\nprivate static int SomethingElse() => 42;\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2777, 2778], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2777, 2778], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="If we look at the assembly code generated for Compute1 on .NET 6, it looks like what we'd hope for. We're adding Value 5 times, Value is trivially inlined and returns a constant value 16, and so we'd hope that the assembly code generated for Compute1 would effectively just be returning the value 80 (hex 0x50), which is exactly what happens:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="If we look at the assembly code generated for Compute1 on .NET 6, it looks like what we'd hope for. We're adding Value 5 times, Value is trivially inlined and returns a constant value 16, and so we'd hope that the assembly code generated for Compute1 would effectively just be returning the value 80 (hex 0x50), which is exactly what happens:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2779, 2785], level=0, children=None, content='; Program.Compute1()\n mov eax,50\n ret\n; Total bytes of code 6\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2786, 2787], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2786, 2787], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="But Compute2 is a bit different. The structure of the code is such that the additional call to SomethingElse ends up slightly perturbing something about the JIT's analysis, and .NET 6 ends up with this assembly code:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="But Compute2 is a bit different. The structure of the code is such that the additional call to SomethingElse ends up slightly perturbing something about the JIT's analysis, and .NET 6 ends up with this assembly code:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2788, 2801], level=0, children=None, content='; Program.Compute2()\n sub rsp,28\n call Program.SomethingElse()\n add eax,10\n add eax,10\n add eax,10\n add eax,10\n add eax,10\n add rsp,28\n ret\n; Total bytes of code 29\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2802, 2803], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2802, 2803], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="Rather than a single mov eax, 50 to put the value 0x50 into the return register, we have 5 separate add eax, 10 to build up that same 0x50 (80) value. That's… not ideal.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="Rather than a single mov eax, 50 to put the value 0x50 into the return register, we have 5 separate add eax, 10 to build up that same 0x50 (80) value. That's… not ideal.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2804, 2805], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2804, 2805], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="It turns out that many of the JIT's optimizations operate on the tree data structures created as part of parsing the IL. In some cases, optimizations can do better when they're exposed to more of the program, in other words when the tree they're operating on is larger and contains more to be analyzed. However, various operations can break up these trees into smaller, individual ones, such as with temporary variables created as part of inlining, and in doing so can inhibit these operations. Something is needed in order to effectively stitch these trees back together, and that's forward substitution. You can think of forward substitution almost like an inverse of CSE; rather than trying to find duplicate expressions and eliminate them by computing the value once and storing it into a temporary, forward substitution eliminates that temporary and effectively moves the expression tree into its use site. Obviously you don't want to do this if it would then negate CSE and result in duplicate work, but for expressions that are defined once and used once, this kind of forward propagation is valuable. ", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/61023'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#61023', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' added an initial limited version of forward substitution, and then ', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/63720'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#63720', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' added a more robust generalized implementation. Subsequently, ', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/70587'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#70587', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' expanded it to also cover some SIMD vectors, and then ', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/71161'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#71161', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' improved it further to enable substitutions into more places (in this case into call arguments). And with those, our silly benchmark now produces the following on .NET 7:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="It turns out that many of the JIT's optimizations operate on the tree data structures created as part of parsing the IL. In some cases, optimizations can do better when they're exposed to more of the program, in other words when the tree they're operating on is larger and contains more to be analyzed. However, various operations can break up these trees into smaller, individual ones, such as with temporary variables created as part of inlining, and in doing so can inhibit these operations. Something is needed in order to effectively stitch these trees back together, and that's forward substitution. You can think of forward substitution almost like an inverse of CSE; rather than trying to find duplicate expressions and eliminate them by computing the value once and storing it into a temporary, forward substitution eliminates that temporary and effectively moves the expression tree into its use site. Obviously you don't want to do this if it would then negate CSE and result in duplicate work, but for expressions that are defined once and used once, this kind of forward propagation is valuable. [dotnet/runtime#61023](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/61023) added an initial limited version of forward substitution, and then [dotnet/runtime#63720](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/63720) added a more robust generalized implementation. Subsequently, [dotnet/runtime#70587](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/70587) expanded it to also cover some SIMD vectors, and then [dotnet/runtime#71161](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/71161) improved it further to enable substitutions into more places (in this case into call arguments). And with those, our silly benchmark now produces the following on .NET 7:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2806, 2811], level=0, children=None, content='; Program.Compute2()\n sub rsp,28\n call qword ptr [7FFCB8DAF9A8]\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2812, 2818], level=0, children=None, content=' add eax,50\n add rsp,28\n ret\n; Total bytes of code 18\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='heading_open', tag='h4', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2819, 2820], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='####', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2819, 2820], level=1, children=[Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<span id="page-58-0">', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='</span>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='strong_open', tag='strong', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='**', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='Vectorization', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='strong_close', tag='strong', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='**', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='<span id="page-58-0"></span>**Vectorization**', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='heading_close', tag='h4', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='####', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2821, 2822], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2821, 2822], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='SIMD, or Single Instruction Multiple Data, is a kind of processing in which one instruction applies to multiple pieces of data at the same time. You\'ve got a list of numbers and you want to find the index of a particular value? You could walk the list comparing one element at a time, and that would be fine functionally. But what if in the same amount of time it takes you to read and compare one element, you could instead read and compare two elements, or four elements, or 32 elements? That\'s SIMD, and the art of utilizing SIMD instructions is lovingly referred to as "vectorization," where operations are applied to all of the elements in a "vector" at the same time.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='SIMD, or Single Instruction Multiple Data, is a kind of processing in which one instruction applies to multiple pieces of data at the same time. You\'ve got a list of numbers and you want to find the index of a particular value? You could walk the list comparing one element at a time, and that would be fine functionally. But what if in the same amount of time it takes you to read and compare one element, you could instead read and compare two elements, or four elements, or 32 elements? That\'s SIMD, and the art of utilizing SIMD instructions is lovingly referred to as "vectorization," where operations are applied to all of the elements in a "vector" at the same time.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2823, 2824], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2823, 2824], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='.NET has long had support for vectorization in the form of Vector', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=', which is an easy-to-use type with first-class JIT support to enable a developer to write vectorized implementations. One of Vector', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="'s greatest strengths is also one of its greatest weaknesses. The type is designed to adapt to whatever width vector instructions are available in your hardware. If the machine supports 256-bit width vectors, great, that's what Vector", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=" will target. If not, if the machine supports 128-bit width vectors, great, that's what Vector", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' targets. But that flexibility comes with various downsides, at least today; for example, the operations you can perform on a Vector', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' end up needing to be agnostic to the width of the vectors used, since the width is variable based on the hardware on which the code actually runs. And that means the operations that can be exposed on Vector', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=" are limited, which in turn limits the kinds of operations that can be vectorized with it. Also, because it's only ever a single size in a given process, some data set sizes that fall in between 128 bits and 256 bits might not be processed as well as you'd hope. You write your Vector", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<byte>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='-based algorithm, and you run it on a machine with support for 256-bit vectors, which means it can process 32 bytes at a time, but then you feed it an input with 31 bytes. Had Vector', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=" mapped to 128-bit vectors, it could have been used to improve the processing of that input, but as its vector size is larger than the input data size, the implementation ends up falling back to one that's not accelerated. There are also issues related to R2R and Native AOT, since ahead-of-time compilation needs to know in advance what instructions should be used for Vector", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' operations. You already saw this earlier when discussing the output of DOTNET_JitDisasmSummary; we saw that the NarrowUtf16ToAscii method was one of only a few methods that was JIT compiled in a "hello, world" console app, and that this was because it lacked R2R code due to its use of Vector', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='.NET has long had support for vectorization in the form of Vector<T>, which is an easy-to-use type with first-class JIT support to enable a developer to write vectorized implementations. One of Vector<T>\'s greatest strengths is also one of its greatest weaknesses. The type is designed to adapt to whatever width vector instructions are available in your hardware. If the machine supports 256-bit width vectors, great, that\'s what Vector<T> will target. If not, if the machine supports 128-bit width vectors, great, that\'s what Vector<T> targets. But that flexibility comes with various downsides, at least today; for example, the operations you can perform on a Vector<T> end up needing to be agnostic to the width of the vectors used, since the width is variable based on the hardware on which the code actually runs. And that means the operations that can be exposed on Vector<T> are limited, which in turn limits the kinds of operations that can be vectorized with it. Also, because it\'s only ever a single size in a given process, some data set sizes that fall in between 128 bits and 256 bits might not be processed as well as you\'d hope. You write your Vector<byte>-based algorithm, and you run it on a machine with support for 256-bit vectors, which means it can process 32 bytes at a time, but then you feed it an input with 31 bytes. Had Vector<T> mapped to 128-bit vectors, it could have been used to improve the processing of that input, but as its vector size is larger than the input data size, the implementation ends up falling back to one that\'s not accelerated. There are also issues related to R2R and Native AOT, since ahead-of-time compilation needs to know in advance what instructions should be used for Vector<T> operations. You already saw this earlier when discussing the output of DOTNET\\_JitDisasmSummary; we saw that the NarrowUtf16ToAscii method was one of only a few methods that was JIT compiled in a "hello, world" console app, and that this was because it lacked R2R code due to its use of Vector<T>.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2825, 2826], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2825, 2826], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='Starting in .NET Core 3.0, .NET gained literally thousands of new "hardware intrinsics" methods, most of which are .NET APIs that map down to one of these SIMD instructions. These intrinsics enable an expert to write an implementation tuned to a specific instruction set, and if done well, get the best possible performance, but it also requires the developer to understand each instruction set and to implement their algorithm for each instruction set that might be relevant, e.g. an AVX2 implementation if it\'s supported, or an SSE2 implementation if it\'s supported, or an ArmBase implementation if it\'s supported, and so on.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='Starting in .NET Core 3.0, .NET gained literally thousands of new "hardware intrinsics" methods, most of which are .NET APIs that map down to one of these SIMD instructions. These intrinsics enable an expert to write an implementation tuned to a specific instruction set, and if done well, get the best possible performance, but it also requires the developer to understand each instruction set and to implement their algorithm for each instruction set that might be relevant, e.g. an AVX2 implementation if it\'s supported, or an SSE2 implementation if it\'s supported, or an ArmBase implementation if it\'s supported, and so on.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2827, 2828], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2827, 2828], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='.NET 7 has introduced a middle ground. Previous releases saw the introduction of the Vector128', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' and Vector256', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<T>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=" types, but purely as the vehicle by which data moved in and out of the hardware intrinsics, since they're all tied to specific width vectors. Now in .NET 7, exposed via", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content=".NET 7 has introduced a middle ground. Previous releases saw the introduction of the Vector128<T> and Vector256<T> types, but purely as the vehicle by which data moved in and out of the hardware intrinsics, since they're all tied to specific width vectors. Now in .NET 7, exposed via", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[2829, 2830], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[2829, 2830], level=1, children=[Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/53450'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#53450,', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' ', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/63414'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#63414,', markup='', info='', m