e tin, it really is native. After publishing the app, there is no IL involved, and there's no JIT that could even process it. This makes some of the other investments in .NET 7 all the more valuable, for example everywhere investments are happening in source generators. Code that previously relied on reflection emit for good performance will need another scheme. We can see that, for example, with Regex. Historically for optimal throughput with Regex, it's been recommended to use RegexOptions.Compiled, which uses reflection emit at run-time to generate an optimized implementation of the specified pattern. But if you look at the implementation of the Regex constructor, you'll find this nugget:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[3543, 3549], level=0, children=None, content='if (RuntimeFeature.IsDynamicCodeCompiled)\n{\n factory = Compile(pattern, tree, options, matchTimeout != InfiniteMatchTimeout);\n}\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[3550, 3551], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[3550, 3551], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="With the JIT, IsDynamicCodeCompiled is true. But with Native AOT, it's false. Thus, with Native AOT and Regex, there's no difference between specifying RegexOptions.Compiled and not, and another mechanism is required to get the throughput benefits promised by RegexOptions.Compiled. Enter [GeneratedRegex(...)], which, along with the new regex source generator shipping in the .NET 7", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="With the JIT, IsDynamicCodeCompiled is true. But with Native AOT, it's false. Thus, with Native AOT and Regex, there's no difference between specifying RegexOptions.Compiled and not, and another mechanism is required to get the throughput benefits promised by RegexOptions.Compiled. Enter [GeneratedRegex(...)], which, along with the new regex source generator shipping in the .NET 7", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[3552, 3553], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[3552, 3553], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='SDK, emits C# code into the assembly using it. That C# code takes the place of the reflection emit that would have happened at run-time, and is thus able to work successfully with Native AOT.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='SDK, emits C# code into the assembly using it. That C# code takes the place of the reflection emit that would have happened at run-time, and is thus able to work successfully with Native AOT.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[3554, 3566], level=0, children=None, content='private static readonly string s_haystack = new\nHttpClient().GetStringAsync("https://www.gutenberg.org/files/1661/1661-0.txt").Result;\nprivate Regex _interpreter = new Regex(@"^.*elementary.*$", RegexOptions.Multiline);\nprivate Regex _compiled = n