={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<byte>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='. If you write:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='Arguably the biggest improvement around UTF8 in .NET 7 is the new C# 11 support for UTF8 literals. Initially implemented in the C# compiler in [dotnet/roslyn#58991,](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/58991) with follow-on work in [dotnet/roslyn#59390,](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/59390) [dotnet/roslyn#61532,](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/61532) and [dotnet/roslyn#62044,](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/62044) UTF8 literals enables the compiler to perform the UTF8 encoding into bytes at compile-time. Rather than writing a normal string, e.g. "hello", a developer simply appends the new u8 suffix onto the string literal, e.g. "hello"u8. At that point, this is no longer a string. Rather, the natural type of this expression is a ReadOnlySpan<byte>. If you write:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[4717, 4720], level=0, children=None, content='public static ReadOnlySpan<byte> Text => "hello"u8;\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[4721, 4722], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[4721, 4722], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='the C# compiler will compile that equivalent to if you wrote:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='the C# compiler will compile that equivalent to if you wrote:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[4723, 4728], level=0, children=None, content="public static ReadOnlySpan<byte> Text =>\n new ReadOnlySpan<byte>(new byte[] { (byte)'h', (byte)'e', (byte)'l', (byte)'l', \n(byte)'o', (byte)'\\0' }, 0, 5);\n", markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[4729, 4730], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[4729, 4730], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='In other words, the compiler is doing the equivalent of Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes at compile-time and hardcoding the resulting bytes, saving the cost of performing that encoding at run-time. Of course, at first glance, that array allocation might look terribly inefficient. However, looks can be deceiving, and are in this case. For several releases now, when the C# compiler sees a byte[] (or sbyte[] or bool[]) being initialized with a constant length and constant values and immediately cast to or used to construct a ReadOnlySpan', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<byte>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=", it optimizes away the byte[] allocation. Instead, it blits the data for that span into the assembly's data section, and then constructs a span that points directly to that data in the loaded assembly. This is the actual generated IL for the above property:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="In other words, the compiler is doing the equivalent of Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes at compile-time and hardcoding the resulting bytes, saving the cost of performing that encoding at run-time. Of course, at first glance, that array allocation might look terribly inefficient. However, looks can be deceiving, and are in this case. For several releases now, when the C# compiler sees a byte[] (or sbyte[] or bool[]) being initialized with a constant length and constant values and immediately cast to or used to construct a ReadOnlySpan<byte>, it optimizes away the byte[] allocation. Instead, it blits the data for that span into the assembly's data section, and then constructs a span that points directly to that data in the loaded assembly. This is the actual generated IL for the above property:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[4731, 4740], level=0, children=None, content="IL_0000: ldsflda valuetype '<PrivateImplementationDetails>'/'__StaticArrayInitTypeSize=6' \n'<PrivateImplementationDetails>'::F3AEFE62965A91903610F0E23CC8A69D5B87CEA6D28E75489B0D2CA02\nED7993C\nIL_0005: ldc.i4.5\nIL_0006: newobj instance void valuetype \n[System.Runtime]System.ReadOnlySpan`1<uint8>::.ctor(void*, int32)\nIL_000b: ret\n", markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[4741, 4742], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[4741, 4742], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="Th