e bounds that are then always 0 and span.Length.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content='[dotnet/runtime#66129,](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/66129) [dotnet/runtime#66178,](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/66178) and [dotnet/runtime#72728,](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/72728) all of which clean up unnecessary checks against the bounds that are then always 0 and span.Length.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[5558, 5559], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[5558, 5559], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="Ok, so the engines are now able to be handed span inputs and process them, great, what can we do with that? Well, Regex.IsMatch is easy: it's not encumbered by needing to perform multiple matches, and thus doesn't need to worry about how to store that input ReadOnlySpan", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<char>', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' for the next match. Similarly, the new Regex.Count, which provides an optimized implementation for counting how many matches there are in the input, can bypass using Match or MatchCollection, and thus can easily operate over spans as well; ', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/64289'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#64289', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' added string-based overloads, and ', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/66026'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#66026', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=" added span-based overloads. We can optimize Count further by passing additional information into the engines to let them know how much information they actually need to compute. For example, I noted previously that NonBacktracking is fairly pay-for-play in how much work it needs to do relative to what information it needs to gather. It's cheapest to just determine whether there is a match, as it can do that in a single forward pass through the input. If it also needs to compute the actual starting and ending bounds, that requires another reverse pass through some of the input. And if it then also needs to compute capture information, that requires yet another forward pass based on an NFA (even if the other two were DFA-based). Count needs the bounds information, as it needs to know where to start looking for the next match, but it doesn't need the capture information, since none of that capture information is handed back to the caller. ", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/68242'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#68242', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' updates the engines to receive this additional information, such that methods like Count can be made more efficient.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="Ok, so the engines are now able to be handed span inputs and process them, great, what can we do with that? Well, Regex.IsMatch is easy: it's not encumbered by needing to perform multiple matches, and thus doesn't need to worry about how to store that input ReadOnlySpan<char> for the next match. Similarly, the new Regex.Count, which provides an optimized implementation for counting how many matches there are in the input, can bypass using Match or MatchCollection, and thus can easily operate over spans as well; [dotnet/runtime#64289](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/64289) added string-based overloads, and [dotnet/runtime#66026](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/66026) added span-based overloads. We can optimize Count further by passing additional information into the engines to let them know how much information they actually need to compute. For example, I noted previously that NonBacktracking is fairly pay-for-play in how much work it needs to do relative to what information it needs to gather. It's cheapest to just determine whether there is a match, as it can do that in a single forward pass through the input. If it also needs to compute the actual starting and ending bounds, that requires another reverse pass through some of the input. And if it then also needs to compute capture information, that requires yet another forward pass based on an NFA (even if the other two were DFA-based). Count needs the bounds information, as it needs to know where to start looking for the next match, but it doesn't need the capture information, since none of that capture information is handed back to the caller. [dotnet/runtime#68242](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/68242) updates the engines to receive this additional information, such that methods like Count can be made more efficient.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[5560, 5561], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[5560, 5561], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="So, IsMatch and Count can work with spans. But we still don't have a method that lets you actually get back that match information. Enter the new EnumerateMatches method, added by ", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_open', tag='a', nesting=1, attrs={'href': 'https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/67794'}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=1, children=None, content='dotnet/runtime#67794.', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='link_close', tag='a', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content=' EnumerateMatches is very similar to Match, except instead of handing back a Match class instance, it hands back a ref struct enumerator:', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="So, IsMatch and Count can work with spans. But we still don't have a method that lets you actually get back that match information. Enter the new EnumerateMatches method, added by [dotnet/runtime#67794.](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/67794) EnumerateMatches is very similar to Match, except instead of handing back a Match class instance, it hands back a ref struct enumerator:", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='fence', tag='code', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[5562, 5573], level=0, children=None, content='public ref struct ValueMatchEnumerator\n{\n private readonly Regex _regex;\n private readonly ReadOnlySpan<char> _input;\n private ValueMatch _current;\n private int _startAt;\n private int _prevLen;\n ...\n}\n', markup='```', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_open', tag='p', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[5574, 5575], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[5574, 5575], level=1, children=[Token(type='text', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content="Being a ref struct, the enumerator is able to store a reference to the input span, and is thus able to iterate through matches, which are represented by the ValueMatch ref struct. Notably, today ValueMatch doesn't provide capture information, which also enables it to partake in the optimizations previously mentioned for Count. Even if you have an input string, EnumerateMatches is thus a way to have ammortized allocation-free enumeration of all matches in the input. In .NET 7, though, there isn't a way to have such allocation-free enumeration if you also need all the capture data. That's something we'll investigate designing in the future if/as needed.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False)], content="Being a ref struct, the enumerator is able to store a reference to the input span, and is thus able to iterate through matches, which are represented by the ValueMatch ref struct. Notably, today ValueMatch doesn't provide capture information, which also enables it to partake in the optimizations previously mentioned for Count. Even if you have an input string, EnumerateMatches is thus a way to have ammortized allocation-free enumeration of all matches in the input. In .NET 7, though, there isn't a way to have such allocation-free enumeration if you also need all the capture data. That's something we'll investigate designing in the future if/as needed.", markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='paragraph_close', tag='p', nesting=-1, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='heading_open', tag='h4', nesting=1, attrs={}, map=[5576, 5577], level=0, children=None, content='', markup='####', info='', meta={}, block=True, hidden=False), Token(type='inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=[5576, 5577], level=1, children=[Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0, children=None, content='<span id="page-142-0">', markup='', info='', meta={}, block=False, hidden=False), Token(type='html_inline', tag='', nesting=0, attrs={}, map=None, level=0